The day passed – day! There was no day; it had vanished as quickly as it had come – and night fell again; a night so long yet so brief; long in its terrible silence and brief in its fleeting hours.

A few years ago, I worked as a tutor in an after-school program for elementary school students. I did my best to help them in any subject they struggled with, though my strengths were in English and reading. One of the teachers recruited me to help a young boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade) who was having significant difficulties with reading. I realized something wasn't quite right; he was experiencing the most unusual problems. He could pronounce some letters perfectly, while others were completely foreign to him - it was quite puzzling. While he was clearly of Latino heritage and spoke perfect English, we continued to struggle until I met his mother. One day, while supervising a few remaining students during a field trip day, his mother came in. She didn't speak any English, only Spanish. Despite my limited Spanish knowledge (I was just learning), we managed to communicate. That's when it hit me like lightning: Adrian could read perfectly well, he just wasn't familiar with the English alphabet.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier challenges in schools, particularly in California, and to demonstrate that these issues aren't always obvious. Even for children who speak perfect English, reading can present significant obstacles. While we all acknowledge this problem exists, what's the solution? In Adrian's case, the answer was relatively straightforward: tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for many children who barely speak English, the solution is far more complex. No single approach - whether dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, or ESL classes - can solve this alone. The key lies in combining all these methods.

The dual language system, in particular, is an excellent concept - not just for native Spanish speakers, but for all children. Research shows that students in two-way bilingual education programs often outperform their peers academically. While some fear this approach wastes resources or won't benefit the majority of students, this is incorrect. If we implemented these programs as the standard rather than the exception, all children would benefit. Does this mean requiring all teachers to be bilingual? No, that would be unreasonable and impractical. However, there's no reason we can't have bilingual teaching assistants and tutors to support this approach.

From childhood on, most of us are told that there is something greater than ourselves, greater than we can comprehend. Some of us are sent to Sunday school, others go to temple, or search for answers within themselves. Many of us readily accept the religions passed down to us by our parents. Some, however, reject them completely, denying that there could be anything beyond the knowable in our own egocentric universe. We might adopt one value system, only to later change our minds and replace it with another. Whatever path we choose, we journey to define a part of ourselves through our own unique perspectives on spirituality. We search for a light in the darkness to guide us from the shadows into the sun.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him about his favorite bird. We sat on the front porch of our house, listening to the rain drumming on the tin roof above while smoking our cigarettes together. The gutters channeled the rain down, drowning the plants along the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain with a look that seemed half searching, half remembering. He had grown thinner in recent months, his clothes hanging loosely from his frame. His hair had thinned too, sparser than I remembered. He continued staring into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, scared, and unable to tell my father how much I would miss him because talking about it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer to his, and joined him in watching the falling rain in the June twilight.

My father died that December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation hadn't eased his suffering, but kept him alive a few months beyond the doctors' predictions; I couldn't determine the value of this when it merely prolonged his suffering. What kind of God would do this, I wondered. Alone in the night, I offered no prayers. If God existed, I thought, He had stopped listening to me long ago.

I hadn't wanted to watch him pass from this life into another. So I didn't. I couldn't bear to witness the ending of the life that had created mine. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, better than his family did, and knew Dad wouldn't want his only child to be a spectator at his death. I curled up in my bed for three days and waited for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate of Republicanism. Although primarily a farmer, this profession combined with his brief political career shaped him into a man known for his commitment and candor in matters of personal liberty and governance. His devotion to an agricultural system formed the foundation for virtually all his views on government. His efforts to preserve and promote what he considered the most noble of all professions influenced his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

He believed that the United States had a unique opportunity to create an ideal system, free from the constraints of established traditions, thus enabling true self-governance. Taylor held strong convictions about natural human rights, arguing that these rights were interconnected—if one was compromised, all would eventually fail, diminishing the value of those remaining. Therefore, these rights should remain beyond government reach. He argued against what some termed the "state of nature," where physical strength and cunning intelligence prevailed, asserting that civilization must operate differently.

Taylor maintained that an effective government must acknowledge both the virtuous and corrupt aspects of human nature. He held firm to his dualistic view of morality, asserting that "Since government is administered by humans, all its virtues and vices must be human." He identified positive principles as those protecting private property, advancing agriculture, and limiting capitalism, believing that a government founded on such principles would function justly regardless of its leadership, which he saw as inevitably driven by self-interest and greed. While he viewed self-interest as humanity's universal motivator, he considered it harmful only when it led to the formation of privileged groups thriving at others' expense.

As a dedicated Republican of his era, Taylor advocated for strict constitutional interpretation. He favored a highly limited federal government, restricted to powers explicitly granted by the Constitution. He recognized that an expansive federal government would be costly and potentially tyrannical. However, he warned against overly literal interpretation, arguing that understanding the framers' intent was crucial to prevent corruption. Notably, he regarded the Declaration of Independence as the nation's true founding document, as it more clearly depicted the United States as a union of sovereign states rather than a single unified nation.

Downward I gazed, my mind barely processing the sight before me. With detached precision and practiced awareness, I analyzed the scene, refusing to connect it to any deeper meaning. Thoughts flickered through my consciousness, appearing and vanishing almost instantaneously. My mind worked with such fluid efficiency that it seemed I wasn't truly thinking, just experiencing what lay before me.

Once, following an artist's recommendation, I bought a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." Since age six, I'd wanted to learn drawing, and this book covered everything from basic pencil handling to how the brain processes visual information. One key technique involved placing a frame around the subject, transforming complex scenes - like a fruit bowl in a kitchen connected to a dining room - into manageable, focused compositions.

In this moment, however, I couldn't mentally impose such a frame. The sight before me was too overwhelming, too striking in its crude reality. While Picasso had his Blue Period, Monet his gardens, and Renaissance masters their vibrant palettes, here I stood, facing what could only be called my "Work in Brown."

My fingers gripped my chosen tool, muscles tensing and relaxing as I moved, transforming intention into action in what might have been my most memorable creative moment, though not for the reasons I'd ever imagined. Water swirled peacefully, crystal clear at first. Particles separated and drifted away. With increasing urgency, my hand pushed the handle again, but the stubborn brown mass remained fixed to the toilet's bottom, unmoved and defiant.

Standing there in my work uniform, green tie uncomfortably tight, mop in hand, I contemplated this unwelcome gift left by some inconsiderate patron of Rite Aid's restroom. After several more futile flushes and moments of philosophical reflection, I reached for the toilet paper, wrapping my hand until it resembled a makeshift protective glove. Then, like a cook retrieving a roast from the oven, I steeled myself for the unpleasant task ahead...

Teenagers are losing their lives behind the wheel. Multiple factors combine to create this deadly statistical pattern for America's youngest drivers. The National Institutes of Health explain that one aspect of the problem lies in the fact that the adolescent brain is literally not prepared for the dangers of driving. Lack of experience is also at the core of the problem. This inexperience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also results in higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and running off the road.

Teenagers face significantly greater risks when traveling with their peers—something anyone with common sense knows happens regularly. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study demonstrating a clear correlation between passenger age and traffic accident frequency.

California and other states have tried to enhance teen driver safety by implementing provisional licenses that restrict driving hours and prohibit minor passengers. However, in my view, provisional licenses are merely temporary solutions. The fundamental issue is that—as a group—the youngest drivers are, by all statistical measures, simply unable to adequately manage the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes that even 18 is too young for a standard driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research indicates a common tendency among those under 19-20 to seek risks purely for the thrill.

It therefore makes sense to postpone driving until this thrill-seeking tendency begins to diminish. If we continue issuing licenses to young teens, we'll not only continue to witness deadly accidents but likely see the death toll rise to alarming levels in coming years. By 2010, the children of Baby-Boomers will be eligible to drive, putting millions of new teen drivers on the road.

Legislation addressing this issue could be relatively straightforward. Schools could continue offering driver's education to prepare future drivers, but no one under 18 would be permitted to operate a motor vehicle. A provisional permit system could remain in place before granting full licenses, along with required practical training hours. These requirements could be based on existing state standards (California, for instance, requires 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of supervised practice). Since teen driving statistics show similar patterns across all states, uniform national legislation would be a reasonable and potentially effective approach to protecting teens nationwide.

This legislative proposal is not a new concept.

This paper addresses three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Initially, a brief definition of the disorder is presented. Subsequently, the diagnostic process is explained, including common characteristics and warning signs. Finally, the paper discusses ways in which teachers can support students with CAPD in an integrated classroom setting.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), describes how effectively the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. In specific terms, it refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the underlying neurobiological activity that generates electrophysiological auditory potentials. Individuals with CAPD have normal hearing capabilities but are not considered hearing impaired; rather, the brain regions responsible for processing auditory input, such as distinguishing words or separating conversation from background noise, do not function typically.

The condition was first documented in the mid-1950s under the term "auditory imperception" during studies of children with communication disorders. Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari pioneered testing methods in 1954, followed by Kimura's introduction of dichotic testing in 1961, which established a model explaining the physiology of auditory perception. A significant national conference in 1977 sparked increased research into CAPD in children.

CAPD manifests in various ways: affected individuals may struggle with sound localization, difficulty distinguishing between multiple sound events, inability to recognize sound patterns, challenges in detecting vocal nuances (such as sarcasm), auditory masking, difficulty synthesizing sound information meaningfully, and problems processing the sequence of auditory information.

Diagnosis requires systematic evaluation of listening behavior and performance on auditory function tests, conducted by professionals including audiologists, speech-language pathologists, and psychologists. The assessment may involve questionnaires, behavioral observation, and various auditory skill evaluations. Currently, there is no single standardized diagnostic tool with consistent success rates, and the disorder's cause remains unknown. Many diagnostic procedures involve testing the patient's ability to differentiate between simultaneous auditory stimuli, while advanced methods include measuring acoustic responses within the ear.

In pursuing my studies in social work, I aim to build a career with the Department of Family and Children Services to assist abused or neglected children and support troubled families. The values I can bring to social work include: service, respect, ethical conduct, dedication to improving relationships between others, and commitment to my own professional development to maintain competence in my field. These core values aren't just important for social workers; they're personally important to me.

I've always wanted to help others, though I was uncertain about my career path. During my high school and college years, I witnessed many people running from their problems, with some using less-than-ideal coping mechanisms. These experiences led me to pursue a psychology degree. Still uncertain about my career direction, I decided to take a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy sitting on her couch. She explained he was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police to his parents' house. Wanting to help, I drove to his parents' home. There, I privately shared my concerns with the police and mentioned my psychology degree. The police asked me to speak with the parents since there was nothing legally they could do for the teenager. The parents appeared nervous and made excuses to explain their son's "manipulative" behavior in involving outsiders in "simple" disputes.

Another crucial value in social work is social justice. As a society, we claim to value individuality and mourn those we've lost, yet our concept of "individuality" often follows outdated traditions rather than embracing true uniqueness. I am an individual who refuses to limit myself to conform to others' expectations. Throughout my academic years, I protested against social injustice in various ways: dying my hair unconventional colors, wearing clothes that expressed my personality, getting multiple ear piercings, openly participating in GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and fighting against racism and discrimination whenever I encountered it. I believe in social justice and will continue to stand against social injustice.

This paper examines the biological and sociocultural models as they relate to the sleep disorder insomnia. The biological model emphasizes inherited genetic information and medical health aspects, while the sociocultural models examine environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia examines these models and elaborates on selected research findings to better explain the models. The research explanations and their findings are then analyzed critically to identify their specific strengths and limitations.

A sleep disorder can be categorized as either a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder connected to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other conditions. Primary sleep disorders are classified as either Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while sleep disorders linked to other mental disorders are associated with Axis I or Axis II disorders. Additional categories of sleep disorders may result from medical complications or substance use. The Dyssomnias include: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia involves difficulty in achieving or maintaining sleep, Primary Hypersomnia involves difficulty staying awake, both lasting for at least one month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM sleep. While Dyssomnias focus on sleep initiation and maintenance, Parasomnias are sleep disorders characterized by behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological events. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified.

I have been studying at University Park for about two and a half years now, equivalent to four and a half semesters. For many students, including myself, navigating the campus can be challenging. During my freshman year, I was assigned to a dorm in East Halls - practically the easternmost point of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. The journey from my residence in Stuart Hall to classes in distant locations like the Willard building, near campus center, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially in State College's frequently adverse weather conditions.

Speaking with a recent alumnus, I discovered that not long ago, East Halls was separated from the main campus by vast stretches of unused land. Today, that space has been filled with athletic fields, major new buildings including the new Creamery and health services facility, and is surrounded by apartment complexes. As our campus continues to grow, transportation between locations becomes increasingly challenging. What's the best solution to this mobility issue? On a college campus, it's the bicycle. However, the bicycle alone isn't the solution - students need to use them, and the campus infrastructure needs to accommodate cyclists' needs.

I recently spoke with a friend who had returned to cycling after several years. He wondered why he'd ever stopped, saying, "Bicycles are fantastic - there was a period when cycling wasn't considered cool, but it's really the most practical way to get around." Beyond its health benefits, cycling is the most efficient mode of transportation. A simple breakfast and some physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off-campus, just as far from the center as some dorms. Purchasing a bicycle was my wisest decision this year. I have daily classes in Thomas building, normally a twenty-five-minute walk from my residence. By bicycle, I can reduce this to just 5 minutes with sufficient effort. The only challenge is that Pollock Road, while the most direct route to Thomas building from my home, isn't always easy to navigate, whether on foot or by bicycle. While walking has its merits, my schedule is too demanding for it to be practical. Without my bicycle, walking would be my only dependable option for reaching classes. Walking to Thomas daily would consume an additional 30-40 minutes of my time - over two and a half hours weekly. Factor in all the other walking time for various classes, appointments, and other commitments, and it amounts to more time than I can afford to spend.

Aldous Huxley critiques the looming threat of both technology and capitalistic structures through the creation of a dystopia in "Brave New World." In this world, community value supersedes individualism, and citizens are conditioned from birth to prioritize instant gratification above all else. The population serves as mere pawns in a greater scheme, confined within an ideology dictated by the World Controller. When analyzing the work through Marxist theory, one can observe the author's underlying skepticism regarding the development of these systems. Common Marxist concepts such as homogeneity and reification reinforce the notion that Huxley's novel serves as commentary on the flaws in his era's emerging economy.

Capitalism is satirized through the Marxist concept of false consciousness. The general populace remains ignorant of their true economic relationship with other classes, focused solely on personal gain. This results from ideological control of the proletariat and workers, clearly demonstrated through the conditioning in Brave New World. The lower classes - Delta, Gamma, and others - lack genuine free will; through hypnopaedia, their drive to consume, spend, and indulge is artificially enhanced. This manipulation stems from the World Controller's authority. Hegemony - the complete domination of social classes by a select group - is evidently at play. The lower classes remain oblivious to their manipulation, literally buying into an ideology that perpetuates the system. The upper classes possess awareness of this reality but remain passive; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard take meaningful action. Indeed, the class interactions serve as powerful indicators of capitalism's perceived oppression.

Genuine interpersonal relationships are nonexistent in Brave New World. Characters lack depth, even among protagonists, perhaps suggesting Huxley's view that the combination of technology and capitalism strips humanity of free will and expression. Love is absent, as are extreme emotions; instead, interactions remain superficial, illustrated by men's focus on women's physical attributes and women's casual discussion of their encounters. Moreover, each social class's acceptance of their hierarchical position reflects capitalism's socioeconomic impact. Their unwavering adherence to communal roles mirrors Marxist observations about the proletariat, who are falsely convinced of their superiority as long as they continue to consume, conform, and align with their peers.

Nearly four years ago, I enrolled in an Islamic studies course at CBC. One of the main topics of heated debate in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I believe this question is even more pertinent today than ever before. Looking back at events since 9/11, I have personally witnessed mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance for Islam in America. I doubt that in 2001 we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, who has clear Muslim connections in his family background.

The Prophet's Biography fascinates me because, based on what I know of Muhammad's history, the biography contradicts Muhammad's personality. From my previous knowledge and studies, I had understood that Muhammad forced conversions to Islam, conquering tribes and compelling them to adopt the Islamic faith. However, the biography portrays Muhammad as something of a martyr, misunderstood by others and displaying humility, after which people gradually recognized the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

Moreover, there are remarkable parallels between Jesus' ministry and Muhammad's 'miracles.' The most striking example is when he supposedly multiplied mutton and milk to feed more than forty men. This writing style suggests to me that the authors wanted to present Muhammad as a humble prophet who didn't need to prove himself but simply lived in truth and miracles. This kind of narrative particularly troubles me as it seems to diminish Jesus Christ's miracles and life. It appears as though they're appropriating Jesus' life and character through Muhammad.

The biography contains numerous accounts that seem intended to provide 'witness testimony' or examples of people who 'independently' converted to Islam. However, these stories often come from third-hand sources - tales passed down through multiple people. I found this problematic because while it was meant to validate the stories' authenticity, it actually made them less credible and more suspicious.

What disturbs me most about this work is its attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly, humble, endearing, wise, and gentle man. Historical accounts contradict this portrayal of Muhammad as gentle and humble, and I wonder if today's Muslims are aware of the true historical context of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and his convictions during his lifetime were quickly abandoned in the development of Christian thought after his death. Looking at this history in broad strokes, we see Christianity trending increasingly away from its origins. Today's world shows an ever-increasing awareness and unprecedented progressive tendencies. While traditional people remain and will resist thinking beyond what they were taught, this segment of the population may not be influential enough to shape the whole. Among Christians, historical awareness will grow tremendously in the coming years. A desire will emerge to separate the doctrines added to Christianity over time from the original intentions of the religion's founder. Though it may take decades or even centuries, the outcome is inevitable: There will be a great reversal in Christian history's trajectory. There will be a return to its original form. A movement will grow that strips away layers of doctrine, one after another, as if time were moving backward, until only Jesus's original divine message to humanity remains, before other thinkers made their interpretations. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, inspiring masses to worship as in Jesus's time, following only his teachings, the church as an institution will remain strong as a guide. However, as the theological clock turns backward, Christianity's extreme diversity will consolidate into greater uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of all kinds, we will see increasing similarities rather than differences. Human history is full of such great reversals. Consider how Christians were once persecuted and killed by the Roman Empire, which later became a Christian institution. Our nation has progressed from enslaving African-Americans to having African-American leadership. The coming great reversion will unfold within Christianity, undoing history in search of its source, and reducing diversity in the process. Crucially, this process will be enabled by reading Jesus's words metaphorically rather than literally. So what has transpired since Jesus's lifetime? Looking far enough back, we find only Judaism, Christianity's theological foundation. Monotheism, the concept of divine revelation, and the authority of Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion when Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 BCE. The Jewish population was not unified, being divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I believe "The Jungle" demonstrates how humans are inherently greedy and self-centered at their core. They are solely focused on looking after themselves and optimizing their own lives, while showing no concern for those beneath them. "The Jungle" illustrates this in numerous ways, most notably through the behavior of factory owners and managers. Their singular focus is on expanding their companies and factories to their maximum potential, showing complete disregard for anyone or anything that stands in their way or suffers due to their progress. According to Upton Sinclair's depiction, the industrial landscape dominated the sky with its stark buildings and towering chimneys, spewing endless streams of smoke into the distance - a powerful image of environmental devastation and corporate indifference.

The owners and managers showed equal disregard for the workers who generated their wealth. They would take any measure to increase profits or reduce costs, creating an environment that was "a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds" where human value was consistently subordinate to financial gain. Workers faced arbitrary layoffs without notice or compensation, endured grueling hours, and worked in dangerous conditions without any legal protections or safety regulations. Though never explicitly stated, the residents of Packingtown were expected to silently endure both the horrific working conditions in the factories and the squalid living conditions surrounding them. While labor unions existed, they often exploited rather than helped the workers they claimed to represent. The working population, largely comprised of poor immigrants, existed in a state comparable to slavery, perpetually teetering on the edge of starvation and subject to the whims of employers who proved as ruthless as slave drivers of the past. Under such a system, moral degradation became not just likely but inevitable.

Dream-land is considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-proclaimed superior poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe employs the term "Thule" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces to Virgil. Virgil used this term to refer to an island north of Britain that the Greeks considered the edge of the known world. While Virgil's use of the term is certain, there is a more contemporary source that deserves recognition. Poe had a strong interest in German authors.

This reference is significant as it demonstrates Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. In his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," Karl J. Arndt notes the similarities between their poems, concluding that Poe was emulating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a renowned author of the poetic drama Faust, published in two parts - the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe's death, 1832. Within Faust's second part lies a short poem titled "The King of Thule." The poem tells of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. Following her death, he drinks heavily and weeps remembering his dead queen. Deciding his time has come, he bequeaths all his possessions to his children except for the goblet. He then walks to a cliff, casts the goblet into the ocean, closes his eyes, and dies. The King of Thule's disposition and the king's portrayal in Dream-Land bear striking similarities, perhaps representing a dark mirror of Poe's own loss and reliance on alcohol.

Poe mentions Thule twice in his collected works: once as "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and twice in "Dream-Land," bookending the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as complementary works. In "Dream-Land," the speaker depicts Thule's landscape as dark and lonely, haunted by deceased friends, viewing a colorless, shadowed world. These scenes parallel "The King of Thule," where the protagonist has lost his wife, experiences isolation, and loses his will to rule or live. The entire poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's narrative.

Goethe was an influential author whom Poe would have known, if for no other reason than his respect for Tennyson. Beyond the Tennyson connection, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe's work through the numerous reproductions that followed the original publication.

Under California law, the question arises whether a customer who was injured after slipping on spilled applesauce in a grocery store could be awarded punitive damages by demonstrating that the store manager acted maliciously, given that he was notified twice about the spill but failed to have it cleaned for thirty minutes while he was having his dinner.

The judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's punitive damages claim outright. To justify punitive damages, a plaintiff must demonstrate that the defendant acted with willful and conscious disregard for probable harm, and that the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have anticipated the likely harm of leaving a spill uncleaned, especially given that multiple D&D customers had suffered slip-and-fall injuries in previous months. While her argument about the despicable nature of Martin's actions may be less compelling, it remains reasonable considering that six similar incidents occurred in 2009, yet Martin still failed to implement proper safety measures.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 PM, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed his manager Paul Martin about an applesauce spill in one of the aisles. Martin, who was on his dinner break, dismissed the matter, stating he "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." Fifteen minutes later, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also reported the spill, receiving the same response. At 5:30 PM, Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill and suffered a serious back injury. It's worth noting that five other slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D during 2009. Palmer is now pursuing both compensatory and punitive damages, and we are evaluating whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damages claim.

Under California Civil Code § 3294(a), punitive damages may be awarded for non-contractual obligations if the defendant's actions demonstrated "oppression, fraud or malice." The statute defines malicious conduct as either intentionally harmful or, lacking direct intent, "despicable" and executed with "willful and conscious disregard for others' rights or safety." California courts have interpreted malicious conduct as actions taken with conscious disregard when the defendant "was aware of the likely dangerous consequences of their behavior and willfully failed to avoid those consequences."

She had always sensed something was missing in her life. It was an unfulfillable longing that persisted. It began when she was around 14, just entering her teenage years, and remained with her three years later at 17. By then, she had realized she was searching for someone rather than something. Yet no boys caught her interest. Several had been drawn to her, making awkward attempts to court the un-courtable, but none appealed to her. She often questioned this peculiar situation, trying to understand what could cause such an unusual circumstance in a teenage girl. Years of reflection had produced theories, but none satisfactory enough to seriously consider. So she continued living, constantly examining her desires.

A day at home was typically peaceful. Her parents were gentle, composed people who never quarreled with each other and, surprisingly, rarely argued with their daughter. Their only conflicts arose from her assertions of independence and free spirit. Though born to serene parents, she balanced their calm nature with her vibrant and engaging personality, making her well-liked, especially combined with her inherent kindness.

This day, however, was different. As she wandered from room to room, seeking fresh inspiration, she heard her mother's beautiful voice cry out from the kitchen. She rushed in, panic-stricken, calling out, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She found her mother on the floor, clearly in pain, taking short, pained breaths. "Honey," her mother managed between gasps, "I need... hospital." The words came out strained, and her daughter could see she was in severe pain. "Okay Mom, just show me where I can lift you." Her mother guided her hands, and at that moment, the household's hero was thankful for her strength training classes. She carried her mother to the car, carefully laid her in the back seat, and drove.

The hospital visit brought familiar scents of antiseptic and illness, tinged with anxiety. But she noticed none of this, focused entirely on helping her mother. She rushed in carrying the injured woman, calling urgently for medical help. Concerned staff quickly gathered, bringing a gurney where they placed her mother. They whisked her away for immediate examination, leaving her daughter to wait in worried solitude.

It turned out her mother had fallen from a stepstool while reaching for a vase in the highest cabinet.

This research aimed to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," correlates with lower risks of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet represents a modified version of the Mediterranean diet, characterized by increased consumption of plant-based foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes but encompassing fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (in preference to saturated fats) and fish, while reducing intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective studies have shown an inverse relationship between Mediterranean diet adherence and overall cardiovascular (CVD) mortality rates. An intervention trial demonstrated the Mediterranean diet's superiority over low-fat diets in achieving weight loss and improving the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese subjects. However, earlier studies had not specifically examined stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological investigation tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, with no prior history of CVD or diabetes, who participated in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Between 1984 and 2004, researchers calculated aMed diet scores six times using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to evaluate nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of nurses maintained participation throughout the 20-year study period. FFQs underwent validation studies, and reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified through medical records, hospital documentation, autopsies, or death certificates. Cases without available records were classified as "probable" and included, comprising approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions.

To minimize random individual variation and better represent long-term dietary patterns, researchers calculated cumulative averages of the aMed scores from repeated FFQs. The study accounted for potential confounding factors by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, hormone therapy, multivitamin use, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

The findings revealed that greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, indicated by higher aMed scores, was associated with reduced risk of both CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up, researchers documented 2,391 CHD cases, 1,763 stroke cases, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths. Women in the highest aMed quintile showed significantly lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign declares that Hitler lives in Burma.

Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone at a street corner, holding a cardboard sign above her head with this disturbing message written in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation governed by an oppressive military junta that seized power through a coup in 1962. In 2007, several street demonstrations erupted, marking the first public protests in ten years. These protests, led by numerous Burmese monks, became known as "The Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. After the initial uprisings, the general public began taking interest, and while the Burmese government initially reluctantly permitted the monks to hold peaceful gatherings, the situation soon escalated into what some viewed as outright warfare between the monks and the military regime, with forces actively raiding and pillaging monasteries throughout the country. Foreign journalists were immediately arrested, with Japanese photojournalist Kenji Nagai killed on September 27th, 2007, merely for witnessing a street protest. While official figures cite 13 deaths, Colonel Hla Win, who deserted the army days before the official report, stated, "The death toll in recent days far exceeds what's been reported. The number of bodies runs into thousands."

This pattern is nothing unprecedented. While these represent some of the most recent examples of worldwide atrocities, governments' desires to suppress dissent and maintain absolute control over their populations have existed throughout human history. Ancient Roman emperors claimed divine selection for complete authority over their society. Japanese emperors were considered divine beings, supposedly sent to guide their people toward prosperity through developments like Motorola phones and ritual suicide, while our current president, George W. Bush, holds weekly discussions with Ted Haggard, who leads Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary of the Republican Party.

Among the most notorious examples are the June 4th, 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where scholars, workers' rights activists, and students gathered to oppose authoritarian rule. Casualty figures vary dramatically, with official Chinese government reports claiming 200-300 deaths, while Chinese Red Cross reports indicate 2,000-3,000 fatalities. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s represents another instance, where Hutu militias, supported by the Rwandan government, systematically eliminated Tutsis and political moderates regardless of ethnicity. Hitler's Third Reich, spanning multiple years and countries, during which Jewish people were systematically rounded up and killed, stands as another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's jazz legacy stems largely from his longevity and, consequently, his creative ability to shape his orchestra. While Ellington's piano presence remains understated in many of the compositions discussed here, his brilliance as a composer shone through in creating rich, intricate pieces that highlighted his band members' individual talents. He expertly crafted frameworks that allowed soloists to improvise freely, while also composing tightly orchestrated passages that leveraged band members' unique styles to emphasize musical themes. In doing so, he enhanced the orchestra's overall tonality, creating distinctive and cohesive sounds tailored to each piece. His masterful understanding of individual musicians' sounds and their collective harmony in an expanding ensemble enabled him to compose some of jazz history's most groundbreaking works.

The Grove Music dictionary notes Ellington's sonic innovation, particularly referencing Creole Love Call as an example of his pioneering use of voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This early work demonstrates his skill in using vocals to add depth and color without relying on lyrics, while showcasing his ability to complement his soloists' styles - a trait evident throughout his musical journey. This measured twelve-bar blues piece unfolds across six distinct choruses:

[Chorus descriptions remain essentially the same, with minor stylistic variations]

Ellington's innovative use of voice as a tonal element in this piece exemplifies a stylistic signature that runs throughout his work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded the following year, he masterfully combines precise orchestration with his keen sense for tonal color. The interplay between "Bubber" Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing creates a rich harmony by blending Miley's vocal-like playing with Cox's instrumental-style vocals. This approach evolves further in It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), where Ellington showcases Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a cornerstone of his orchestra, introducing the melody with his distinctive muted trombone style.

Why do organisms evolve in the way they do? Are there limitations or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although D'Arcy Thompson declared in 1917 that "even now zoologists have barely begun to dream of defining even the simplest organic forms in mathematical language," the same holds true today. In recent times, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk shell formation through both individual development and evolutionary history (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research investigates how mathematical modeling of developmental and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can help illuminate the mechanisms involved in the direction and scale of evolutionary-developmental changes.

A shell can be understood as a tube-like structure that travels through 360 degrees of space over time. These spiral revolutions of a coiled shell are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the shell's central column, known as the columella. The rate at which the whorls expand can vary, and a continuous line known as the suture separates each whorl. In most shells, the final whorl (body whorl) is the largest. The spire comprises all whorls except the last one. The apex marks the spire's tip, while the opposite end is the base. The animal extends from its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be examined from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural perspectives. (The "standard" orientation shows the shell in an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upward.)

The method for counting whorls begins by viewing the shell from above and identifying where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn to divide the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and are measured to the nearest quarter whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures moving through time and space as the animal builds its shell. It's possible to track the aperture's path using coordinates of each whorl's aperture center and its horizontal and vertical radii. This trajectory can be represented both graphically and mathematically, allowing for parameter variation and modification of mollusk shell development once mathematically formulated.

The infant and child mortality rate in Indonesia has remained relatively stable over the past decade. While the country is progressing toward achieving many Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the improvement rates for child and maternal health fall far short of the progress needed to meet their 2015 targets. The various reasons for these deficiencies will be discussed below, suggesting a need to strengthen the healthcare system rather than focusing on programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has shown progress in increasing the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of births now meeting this standard. However, this category still includes traditional practitioners, such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions in cases of complicated pregnancies (explaining the high percentage of maternal deaths from hemorrhage). In essence, the improvements in this particular indicator are somewhat deceptive, and considerable work remains to be done. Furthermore, there has been a decrease in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five being treated by healthcare professionals. While postnatal care data is incomplete, it's evident that this area is also problematic, with low rates throughout the country.

Cesarean section rates remain lower than expected, at approximately 4%. These rates also highlight another concerning disparity: while urban areas show a 7% c-section rate, rural areas only show 2%. This underscores the issue of inequitable healthcare coverage across the country. Healthcare services are clearly concentrated in urban areas. Another access issue involves vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and wealthiest quintiles. The poor evidently face greater difficulties accessing healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket expenses.

In considering next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the fundamental question is how to most effectively address the service gap. Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing exclusively on pre- and post-pregnancy care? While programmatic approaches to address the above issues are appealing, as they offer more targeted, manageable objectives and typically yield faster results, there are important drawbacks to consider. A major concern is that heavy investment in one particular health sector often depletes funding for other areas and attracts human resources away from other essential services (as seen in the impact of international HIV/AIDS funding on family planning). Additionally, running multiple parallel programs leads to service duplication and lack of coordination, resulting in increased bureaucracy and paperwork for supplies and funding.

The categorization of Popular Music has expanded so dramatically over the last century that it now encompasses such a vast array of genres that creating a definitive list has become nearly impossible. Adding to this complexity, virtually all genres—including rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, to name just a few—have generated multiple sub-genres and even sub-sub-genres within their respective domains.

Heavy Metal rock, in particular, has arguably evolved into one of popular music's most diverse and expressive genres over the past four decades. Its expressiveness stems from its ability to convey a wide spectrum of emotions, though it tends to gravitate toward darker themes. Its diversity emerged shortly after the genre's inception, when artists began to recognize and exploit its inherent flexibility, creating distinct sub-genres that continued to branch into further subdivisions—a process that continues to this day.

Currently, the heavy metal movement has become so nuanced and fragmented that defining its exact nature has become challenging. While it has absorbed influences from numerous other genres, it maintains its own distinct origins. To truly comprehend today's omnipresent metal music, one must understand both the metal movement itself and why it constitutes a movement rather than merely a genre.

Metal is, in many ways, a movement characterized by darkness. It can be viewed as a "music of excess"—greater bass, increased volume, enhanced violence, and heightened theatricality. It eschews primitivism in favor of technical proficiency; metal musicians are notably skilled instrumentalists, a quality that clearly manifests in their music. The movement was significantly influenced by the psychedelic drug culture of the mid-1970s, which led to the creation of increasingly experimental, otherworldly recordings. Metal embraces dark, visceral qualities that were relatively uncommon in popular music of the time, and later generations of metal have drawn inspiration from the dark, visceral elements prevalent in the Romantic Era.

The example of Helter Skelter demonstrates the Beatles' darker side, portraying an up-and-down journey often associated with drug use. Some consider this song one of the first Heavy Metal tracks, created as a response to a similarly heavy Rolling Stones song. The Beatles, seeking to prove they could match the Stones' intensity, included it on The White Album.

Several decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dream-like works, the artist Henri Rousseau was already carefully shaping his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. "The Dream," a 1910 painting by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist, depicts not only a woman overwhelmed by the wonders of the land she visits in her dream but also represents Rousseau's own personal dreams and aspirations as a painter. From the beginning of his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise from other artists and art lovers, finding himself confronted with a difficult internal dilemma in pursuing this goal. "The Dream" is Henri Rousseau's work that best reflects his lifelong inner struggle: whether to conform to or imitate certain painting styles to gain acceptance from the critical art world he so admired, or to allow himself to develop creatively independent and unique, forging his own path as he went.

Before analyzing The Dream from this perspective, one must first understand Rousseau's life story. Born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwestern France, Rousseau came from a middle-class background, his father being a tinsmith and hardware merchant who enjoyed modest prosperity. Having received no formal artistic training, he worked until the age of forty as a gabelou (municipal toll collector) for France, though he was mistakenly nicknamed douanier (customs inspector). The death of his first wife, Clémence, following the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one surviving child, a daughter named Julia, and profound grief. He sought refuge in a new life through painting, which offered him solace and fresh beginnings. Unlike his contemporaries who romanticized peasant life in their paintings, Rousseau was essentially a folk painter who embodied the hopes and dreams of his social class.

Many great thinkers have proposed an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this connection. As John Keats expresses in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - that is all you know on earth, and all you need to know." Much of our life's knowledge comes through education or experience. Yet, as Keats suggests, we seem to grasp ethics and aesthetics without these conventional teaching methods.

Both ethics and aesthetics attempt to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are largely efforts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than providing rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior.

More importantly, critiques of art or morality can never fully capture the essence of what is good or beautiful. While we might discuss the Mona Lisa in terms of foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, these elements alone don't explain what makes it great art. People often preface their analysis of favorite artworks or literature with "There's just something about it" before delving into more detailed explanations. I believe both art and morality resist complete reduction to their component qualities. As Flannery O'Connor notes, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Something transcendent always remains beyond our descriptions of literature, and I believe ethics shares this quality. As Wittgenstein observes, "Ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." This ineffable quality, this je ne sais quoi, is perhaps the most powerful attribute of both art and morality, creating a bridge between them.

I believe morality and art are so closely intertwined because we experience both most powerfully at a noumenal level, to use Kant's terminology. They affect us in ways we can experience but cannot fully explain. This connection is particularly strong in literature. As McKean observes, literature's distinctive feature is its moral quality. While moral standards might not apply to other arts like music, they seem as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living inherently involves values, and literature's significance lies precisely in the values we discover within it.

Today's Germany is regarded as a powerful force, a unified nation with its own cultural blend stretching from the shadows of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This same culture can be experienced from Cologne on the Rhine, through Germany's heartland to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. Given such a distinctive culture, it's not surprising that the Germany we know today emerged from various sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral homeland of the German people. The origin of its name remains highly contested among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed the name came from a Germanic tribe then known as the Tungrians, who were called Germans before crossing the Rhine and engaging in battle with Gallic forces. Julius Caesar first employed the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and fought against Germanic tribes who frequently crossed the Rhine with hostile intentions. He adopted this term from the Gauls themselves, using it to distinguish between those he had conquered (the Gauls) and those he had not. While the origin remains uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gallic language. In the first chapter of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: "The Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (the Gauls) are continuously at war... They engage with the Germans in almost daily battles."

The play Twelfth Night appears to suggest that while disguise can serve as a useful tool for sustaining extended deceptions, one must ultimately shed this newly adopted facade or risk losing their true self in the process. A significant challenge in ending such deception lies in the potential alienation that follows. Thus, one must ultimately choose between preserving their authentic self or maintaining their relationships with others.

The issue of deception through gender role reversal proves particularly complex, raising numerous questions - chief among them being the motivation behind such transformations. In Viola's case, her disguise clearly serves as a means of self-preservation, as evidenced when she states: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count..."

Finding herself in foreign territory, Viola adopts a male persona for protection, though this choice isolates her from potential female allies and support networks. Her convincing performance as a man leads to complicated romantic entanglements, particularly with Olivia's mistaken affections and her own suppressed feelings for Orsino.

For contemporary audiences, Twelfth Night might be interpreted as an exploration of how deception can catalyze the emergence of hidden emotions, particularly in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. While some might question whether Olivia's attraction to Cesario suggests deeper implications about her sexuality, it seems more likely that Shakespeare used this situation to satirize the superficiality of attraction based purely on appearances. This interpretation is supported by how readily Olivia transfers her affections from Cesario to Sebastian, ultimately accepting Viola as family rather than a romantic interest.

German colonial rule has been criticized by various observers for its brutality, particularly regarding the genocide of the Herero and Nama people in German South West Africa. Naturally, such a vast colonial empire cannot be characterized by such a simple description. The German colonial empire exhibited as much diversity in its policies and governing style as it did in its geography. Educational opportunities across the colonies were equally varied. When the British took control of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they discovered a substantial population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Cameroon and other colonies also received praise from contemporary authors.

The situation in South West Africa (today's Namibia) stood in sharp contrast. Unlike East Africa, where the government established state schools and took a leading role in native education, in South West Africa the education of indigenous peoples was left almost entirely to missionary societies with limited government support. The government did, however, invest considerable resources in educating European settlers, establishing state schools and providing stronger support and regulation for missionary schools serving the white population. These educational policies had lasting impacts on South West Africa, even after German rule ended. While other German colonies could boast significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa "the vast majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to South West Africa's divergent experience. This study aims to broaden the discussion by identifying these factors, with particular emphasis on new research regarding the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities toward native Africans.

There is extensive literature on education in the German colonial empire. Most sources are in German and date from the early twentieth century, during or shortly after German colonial rule. Early works primarily aimed to describe the educational systems in these colonies. Later English-language studies expanded the discourse through comparative analyses of education across German colonies and more detailed examinations of specific educational aspects. These studies revealed significant variations in colonial educational systems. Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa most directly addresses this paper's topic. Cohen compares the educational systems of both colonies and examines factors accounting for their differences. According to Cohen, South West Africa's large settler population explains many distinctive features of its educational system.

Compared to Germany's other colonial territories, South West Africa had a relatively temperate climate, although much of the region consists of arid desert. The European population in South West Africa reflected these relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites resided in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in East Africa, the colony with the next largest settler population.

The United States and Mexico exemplify two nations that were once caught in a lasting rivalry spanning 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The pinnacle of this conflict was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States defeated Mexico and acquired Texas and the American Southwest. Numerous other confrontations occurred between the two nations, finally subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry originated from clashes over religion, culture, traditions, and significant material interests.

This pattern mirrors many other nations experiencing enduring rivalries with their neighbors. Countries sharing borders often face conflicting interests that lead to rivalries. The U.S.-Mexico case reflects a common pattern among neighboring nations with sustained conflicts. As David M. Pletcher (1977) noted, "Only Mexico and Cuba presented persistent, overarching diplomatic challenges for America" (p. 41). Indeed, both nations' proximity to the United States contributed to their rival status, while other Latin American countries maintained generally positive relations.

Religious differences created a divide between the nations, a common historical phenomenon. Sally Frahm (2001) observes that "while 20th-century Americans opposed fascism and communism, their 18th and 19th-century counterparts opposed Catholicism and monarchy" (p.86). Similar to how the Cold War combined ideological differences with competition over vital interests, this rivalry centered on religious rather than political differences. The mutual distrust inherited from their former colonial powers - England and Spain - significantly hindered the development of friendly relations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) document 17 disputes during the 57-year rivalry. Most conflicts involved territorial issues, particularly border raids and frontier challenges. Bandit attacks on American border towns remained problematic until both nations established stronger military presence along their borders.

According to Schmitt (1974), the rivalry began to diminish as Mexico became increasingly economically dependent on the United States, and finally concluded when American interests shifted from territorial expansion to economic involvement in Mexico during the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness whose existence I had never known about.

I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply rooted need for security and safety that I lacked as a child. "You'll always find work; people will always get sick" was the mantra I heard repeatedly as I reached adolescence and beyond. So - even though my dream was to be a scientist or journalist - preferably both - I chose nursing.

Nevertheless, there I was: 46 years old and single, with barely any savings and unable to work. To this day I remain disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I literally have nothing left to call my own. I get by, but each day is a battle that challenges my security, safety, and self-worth. While nothing in my life is certain anymore, one truth remains clear: I couldn't have survived all these years without the support of my family and a few good friends, regardless of how strong I was. And trust me, when real disaster strikes, you don't feel strong at all.

My message is that life will always bring emergencies - both major and minor. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well-prepared you are, some challenges are simply too great to face alone.

I completely agree that we in the U.S. need to stop relying solely on big government - heaven knows that basket is moldy and falling apart anyway. But I'd much rather see Americans learning to trust each other again - learning to help one another and to ask for help - rather than each of us retreating to our backyards to build individual fallout shelters.

American Conservatives speak of the "rugged individualism" that built this nation, but in reality, what sustained our ancestors through hard times wasn't individualism - it was compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't reach the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and plastic sheeting with duct tape for windows in case of biological attack. I have multiple flashlights, various batteries, plenty of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods too. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and can preserve your own food - do it. It's an excellent idea, as is having a wood stove, provided you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're doing all that, make sure to get to know your neighbors.

Around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. Throughout his life, he renounced worldly attachments and achieved enlightenment, and his teachings gave rise to Buddhism—with its most orthodox branch known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion, now approximately twenty-five centuries old, appears quite different today than it did during Buddha's lifetime. This transformation is evident everywhere, such as in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, which holds religious significance, despite Buddha never having taught about such festivities. These variations extend from superficial traditions to the soteriological essence of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, from both monastic and lay perspectives, has needed to adapt its doctrinal principles over time, influenced by forces both external and internal, hostile and benign.

Various qualifying terms are essential to this discussion. The concept of internal versus external forces is key: internal forces emerge from members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of their monastic status, while external forces come from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is one that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community—arising from negative perceptions of Buddhism. A benign force neither intends to help nor harm the Buddhist community, though it may inadvertently do either. These distinctions will be referenced throughout this discussion.

To understand these changes, one must first grasp the fundamental doctrines at the heart of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is primarily contained within the Tripitaka—the three baskets of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains the discourses, the Vinaya Pitaka holds the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka encompasses Buddhism's metaphysical aspects. These metaphysical concepts include Anatta (no-self), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Understanding these concepts is crucial for ending Sansara, the continuous cycle of death and rebirth. With the end of Sansara comes the cessation of lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) through enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka establishes life's rules: five precepts for laypeople (abstaining from killing, lying, stealing, sexual misconduct, and intoxicants), while monks follow numerous additional disciplinary rules. At Buddhism's doctrinal core lie the four noble truths, beginning with Dukkha—the truth that life contains suffering, followed by the understanding that attachment causes suffering, and that suffering can be overcome.
